---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Near-Home Parking: Shortest-Path Lot Assignment Model"
  year="2025"
  category="Network Analysis · Urban Parking"
  tools={['Python', 'OSMnx', 'NetworkX', 'GeoPandas', 'QGIS', 'Shortest Path']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Background</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Tel Aviv's "Near-Home Parking" policy gives residents priority overnight access to nearby
        municipal lots. As it expanded, the city needed to decide which streets map to which lot —
        the existing boundaries were hand-drawn and ignored real walking distances. This project
        built a spatial model to assign every street to its nearest lot while balancing demand.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/night-parking-network.png`}
      alt="Three side-by-side panels showing how a lot's initial service area grows with capacity: 250, 350, and 670 spaces — the blue street network and polygon outline expand accordingly"
      class="proj-map proj-map-sm"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Initial service area computation for a single lot, shown at three stages of network expansion
      (250 → 350 → 670 addresses, up to a 750 m walking-distance ceiling). The model grows the
      catchment outward along the street network until it reaches equilibrium — balancing the lot
      against local demand and competing alternatives. A tighter final area signals a high-demand
      location with few nearby options; a larger one reflects lower pressure or more alternatives.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/service_areas.png`}
      alt="Citywide map of Tel Aviv showing model-derived service area polygons for all near-home parking lots as overlapping blue shapes, with lot locations marked in red"
      class="proj-map proj-map-sm proj-map-portrait"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Model-derived service areas across the city. Each polygon is the catchment assigned to one
      lot by the shortest-path model; overlap zones reveal where competing lots split demand.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methodology</h2>
    <ul class="proj-list">
      <li><strong>Street network:</strong> Extracted the pedestrian network from <strong>OpenStreetMap</strong> with <strong>OSMnx</strong>, weighted by real walking distance.</li>
      <li><strong>Shortest-path assignment:</strong> Computed walking distances from every address to all lots with <strong>NetworkX</strong>, assigning each street to its closest option.</li>
      <li><strong>Capacity balancing:</strong> Re-routed overflow demand to the next-nearest lot once capacity was reached, across 12 rounds as new lots joined.</li>
      <li><strong>Load index:</strong> Scored each lot by assigned demand relative to capacity, flagging those under pressure.</li>
      <li><strong>Service areas:</strong> Derived catchment polygons directly from the assignment output, replacing the hand-drawn boundaries.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Results</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        The model's lot assignments and service-area boundaries were <strong>adopted into the
        municipality's production system</strong> — replacing the hand-drawn map as the operational
        basis for the policy citywide.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>

<style>
  :global(.proj-list) {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    max-width: 68ch;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li) {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #2A2A2A;
    padding-left: 1.2em;
    position: relative;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li::before) {
    content: '—';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: #3D5E35;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  :global(.proj-map-sm) {
    max-width: 640px;
  }
  :global(.proj-map-portrait) {
    max-width: 340px;
  }
</style>
